[1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       [1mHostname [22mis used to display the system's DNS name, and to display or set
       its hostname or NIS domain name.

   [1mGET NAME[0m
       When called without any arguments,  the  program  displays  the  current
       names:

       [1mhostname  [22mwill  print the name of the system as returned by the [1mgethost‐[0m
       [1mname[22m(2) function.

       [1mdomainname [22mwill print the NIS domainname of the system.  [1mdomainname [22muses
       the [1mgethostname[22m(2) function, while [1mypdomainname  [22mand  [1mnisdomainname  [22muse
       the [1mgetdomainname[22m(2).

       [1mdnsdomainname  [22mwill  print  the domain part of the FQDN (Fully Qualified
       Domain Name). The complete FQDN of the system is returned with  [1mhostname[0m
       [1m--fqdn [22m(but see the warnings in section [1mTHE FQDN [22mbelow).

   [1mSET NAME[0m
       When  called  with  one argument or with the [1m--file [22moption, the commands
       set the host name or the NIS/YP domain name.  [1mhostname [22muses the [1msethost‐[0m
       [1mname[22m(2) function, while all of the three  [1mdomainname[22m,  [1mypdomainname  [22mand
       [1mnisdomainname  [22muse  [1msetdomainname[22m(2).  Note, that this is effective only
       until the next reboot.  Edit /etc/hostname for permanent change.

       Note, that only the super-user can change the names.

       It is not possible to set the FQDN or the DNS domain name with the  [1mdns‐[0m
       [1mdomainname [22mcommand (see [1mTHE FQDN [22mbelow).

       The host name is usually set once at system startup in [4m/etc/init.d/host‐[0m
       [4mname.sh[24m  (normally  by reading the contents of a file which contains the
       host name, e.g.  [4m/etc/hostname[24m).

   [1mTHE FQDN[0m
       The FQDN (Fully Qualified Domain Name) of the system is  the  name  that
       the  [1mresolver[22m(3) returns for the host name, such as, [4mursula.example.com[24m.
       It is usually the hostname followed by the DNS domain name (the part af‐
       ter the first dot).  You can check the FQDN using [1mhostname --fqdn [22mor the
       domain name using [1mdnsdomainname[22m.

       You cannot change the FQDN with [1mhostname [22mor [1mdnsdomainname[22m.

       The recommended method of setting the FQDN is to make the hostname be an
       alias for the fully qualified name using [4m/etc/hosts[24m, DNS,  or  NIS.  For
       example,  if  the  hostname  was  "ursula",  one  might  have  a line in
       [4m/etc/hosts[24m which reads

              127.0.1.1    ursula.example.com ursula

       Technically: The FQDN is the name [1mgetaddrinfo[22m(3) returns  for  the  host
       name  returned by [1mgethostname[22m(2).  The DNS domain name is the part after
       the first dot.

       Therefore it depends on the configuration of the  resolver  (usually  in
       [4m/etc/host.conf[24m)  how you can change it. Usually the hosts file is parsed
       before DNS or  NIS,  so  it  is  most  common  to  change  the  FQDN  in
       [4m/etc/hosts[24m.

       If  a  machine has multiple network interfaces/addresses or is used in a
       mobile environment, then it may either have multiple FQDNs/domain  names
       or none at all. Therefore avoid using [1mhostname --fqdn[22m, [1mhostname --domain[0m
       and [1mdnsdomainname[22m.  [1mhostname --ip-address [22mis subject to the same limita‐
       tions so it should be avoided as well.

[1mOPTIONS[0m
       [4m-a,[24m [4m--alias[0m
              Display the alias name of the host (if used). This option is dep‐
              recated and should not be used anymore.

       [4m-A,[24m [4m--all-fqdns[0m
              Displays  all  FQDNs  of  the machine. This option enumerates all
              configured network addresses on  all  configured  network  inter‐
              faces,  and  translates  them to DNS domain names. Addresses that
              cannot be translated (i.e. because they do not have an  appropri‐
              ate  reverse IP entry) are skipped. Note that different addresses
              may resolve to the same name, therefore the  output  may  contain
              duplicate entries. Do not make any assumptions about the order of
              the output.

       [4m-b,[24m [4m--boot[0m
              Always set a hostname; this allows the file specified by [4m-F[24m to be
              non-existent  or empty, in which case the default hostname [4mlocal‐[0m
              [4mhost[24m will be used if none is yet set.

       [4m-d,[24m [4m--domain[0m
              Display the name of the DNS domain.  Don't use  the  command  [1mdo‐[0m
              [1mmainname  [22mto get the DNS domain name because it will show the NIS
              domain name and not the DNS domain name.  Use  [1mdnsdomainname  [22min‐
              stead.  See the warnings in section [1mTHE FQDN [22mabove, and avoid us‐
              ing this option.

       [4m-f,[24m [4m--fqdn,[24m [4m--long[0m
              Display the FQDN (Fully Qualified Domain Name). A  FQDN  consists
              of  a short host name and the DNS domain name. Unless you are us‐
              ing bind or NIS for host lookups you can change the FQDN and  the
              DNS  domain  name  (which  is part of the FQDN) in the [4m/etc/hosts[0m
              file. See the warnings in section [1mTHE FQDN [22mabove and use [1mhostname[0m
              [1m--all-fqdns [22minstead wherever possible.

       [4m-F,[24m [4m--file[24m [4mfilename[0m
              Read the host name  from  the  specified  file.  Comments  (lines
              starting with a `#') are ignored.

       [4m-i,[24m [4m--ip-address[0m
              Display  the network address(es) of the host name. Note that this
              works only if the host name can be resolved. Avoid using this op‐
              tion; use [1mhostname --all-ip-addresses [22minstead.

       [4m-I,[24m [4m--all-ip-addresses[0m
              Display all network addresses of the host. This option enumerates
              all configured addresses on all network interfaces. The  loopback
              interface  and IPv6 link-local addresses are omitted. Contrary to
              option [4m-i[24m, this option does not depend on name resolution. Do not
              make any assumptions about the order of the output.

       [4m-s,[24m [4m--short[0m
              Display the short host name. This is the host  name  cut  at  the
              first dot.

       [4m-V,[24m [4m--version[0m
              Print  version  information  on standard output and exit success‐
              fully.

       [4m-y,[24m [4m--yp,[24m [4m--nis[0m
              Display the NIS domain name. If a parameter is given  (or  [1m--file[0m
              [1mname [22m) then root can also set a new NIS domain.

       [4m-h,[24m [4m--help[0m
              Print a usage message and exit.

[1mNOTES[0m
       The  address  families  [1mhostname [22mtries when looking up the FQDN, aliases
       and network addresses of the host are determined by the configuration of
       your resolver.  For instance, on GNU Libc systems, the resolver  can  be
       instructed  to  try  IPv6  lookups  first  by  using the [1minet6 [22moption in
       [1m/etc/resolv.conf[22m.

[1mFILES[0m
       [1m/etc/hostname [22mHistorically this file was supposed to  only  contain  the
       hostname and not the full canonical FQDN. Nowadays most software is able
       to  cope  with  a  full FQDN here. This file is read at boot time by the
       system initialization scripts to set the hostname.

       [1m/etc/hosts [22mUsually, this is where one sets the domain name  by  aliasing
       the host name to the FQDN.

